    <h1><a href="file:/papers/e71b1e7ff859aa4760b2e1510fbf1238.pdf">Participatory
        ergonomics in design processes: The role of boundary objects<br>
      </a></h1>
    <h2>Notes</h2>
    <p>This is the summary of analysis of many Participatory Ergonomics
      activities over many years <em><strong>[wikipedia:The participatory
          approach to ergonomics relies on actively involving workers in
          implementing ergonomic knowledge, procedures and changes with the
          intention of improving working conditions, safety, productivity,
          quality, morale and/or comfort]</strong></em>. </p>
    <p>They group boundary objects encountered in actual PE activities into 5
      categories, then go on to identify 8 qualities which boundary objects may
      have. Many are listed under each category, based on Carlile and Wenger's
      work (except repositories). I have pulled out examples which may need
      special note within Firmware Co-Design (standard examples such as
      diagrams, lists etc have been omitted)</p>
    <ul>
      <li>Repositories (empty set)</li>
      <li>Standardised forms and methods</li>
      <ul>
        <li>Inventory [this could indicate the components of a device, mapping
          hardware/affordance]</li>
        <li>Relations diagram [this could represent orchestrations of
          components]</li>
        <li>Focus group interviews</li>
      </ul>
      <li>Objects, models and maps</li>
      <ul>
        <li>Prototypes [the disclosure and form of the device itself]</li>
        <li>Mannequin [domain specific puppetry such as the paraglider]</li>
        <li>Production games [<span style="text-decoration: underline;">intriguing
            and need to explore</span>]</li>
        <li style="margin-bottom: 0.1em;">Fishbone diagram [planning/logistics/root
          cause, causal diagram to include, People, Methods, Machines, Materials,
          Measurements, Environment]</li>
